<h2>4) Decision tree</h2>
<ul>
  <li>If you support multiple brands with strict boundaries, prioritize workspace isolation and brand-level permissions.</li>
  <li>If your team must provide client-facing QA reports, prioritize exportable analytics and audit-friendly history.</li>
  <li>If agent turnover is high, prioritize training simplicity and macro governance over advanced edge features.</li>
  <li>If chat escalations are frequent, prioritize routing logic and assignment visibility.</li>
  <li>If your process includes external collaborators, ensure role permissions can restrict sensitive actions.</li>
  <li>If you expect rapid account growth, avoid stacks that force manual admin work for every new brand.</li>
</ul>

<h2>5) Top picks breakdown</h2>
<h3>Pick A: Freshdesk multi-brand setup (Best overall)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Agencies balancing capability depth with manageable administration workload.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> You require enterprise-grade custom object/reporting depth immediately.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Broad support features with practical setup effort.</li><li>Strong baseline for multi-brand support operations.</li><li>Good fit for agencies standardizing response workflows.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Configuration complexity can grow quickly.</li><li>Requires active governance to prevent rule sprawl.</li><li>Cross-brand reporting consistency depends on taxonomy discipline.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Define one taxonomy and SLA matrix used by all brands.</li><li>Create macro ownership and approval process.</li><li>Audit routing rules monthly to remove drift.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Zendesk, Intercom.</p>

<h3>Pick B: Help Scout segmented inbox model (Best lean team)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Smaller agencies with fewer brands and emphasis on fast teammate onboarding.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> You need highly complex omnichannel orchestration from launch.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Simple user experience for distributed support teams.</li><li>Lower setup burden for agencies without a full-time admin.</li><li>Encourages clean, process-first operations.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>May require add-ons for advanced enterprise workflows.</li><li>Large multi-brand organizations may outgrow simple controls.</li><li>Complex analytics often need external reporting support.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Use one mailbox per brand and a shared escalation mailbox.</li><li>Standardize saved replies across brands with controlled variants.</li><li>Set weekly quality calibration for cross-brand consistency.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Freshdesk starter build, Front.</p>

<h3>Pick C: Zendesk or Intercom enterprise growth model (Best scaling)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Agencies and in-house multi-brand teams with high channel volume and strict governance needs.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> Your operation is still pre-process and under-resourced administratively.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Supports advanced automation and segmentation strategies.</li><li>Strong ecosystem for integrations and customization.</li><li>Better fit for complex reporting and operational controls.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Longer implementation and training timeline.</li><li>Higher operational overhead to maintain rule quality.</li><li>Risk of overbuilding if core workflow is not standardized first.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Model permission matrix before agent provisioning.</li><li>Create separate QA scorecards by brand tier.</li><li>Pilot one high-volume brand before broad migration.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Freshdesk advanced setup, Front + targeted automations.</p>

